Sure, I can do those things. A couple questions, though:

1. Considering the style of the rest of the code, it seems more consistent for this util fn to not set the `PyErr`, and let the caller choose how to handle what it wants to do between itself and the python layer. So, basically, maybe it should return -1, and allow the caller to set `PyErr` or not.
2. Because there are now 3 possible return values, all the call locations have to change. I can either use an `else if` chain, which requires adding a stack var to hold the return code, or a `switch` statement, which ends up taking a few extra lines. Which would you prefer?

Going from:

```c
if (psutil_pid_exists(pid)) {
  // handle pid existing
} else {
  // handle pid not existing
}
```

to either:

```c
int exists;

...

exists = psutil_pid_exists(pid);
if (exists == 0) {
  // handle pid not existing
} else if (exists == 1) {
  // handle pid existing
} else {
  // handle error
}
```

or:

```c
switch (psutil_pid_exists(pid)) {
case 0:
  // handle pid not existing
  break;
case 1:
  // handle pid existing
  break;
default:
  // handle error
}
```

I actually answered this question on [stackoverflow](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/29873053/how-to-filter-jquery-tablesorter-by-multiple-columns-using-or-logic) ([demo](http://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/4mVfu/4701/))...

```js
$(function () {
    var $table = $('table'),
        // get 'filter-OR' column indexes
        orColumns = $('.filter-OR').map(function (i) {
            return this.cellIndex;
        }).get(),
        filterfxn = function (e, n, f, i, $r, c) {
            var col, v,
                showRow = false,
                content = [];
            $r.children().filter(function (indx) {
                if (orColumns.indexOf(indx) > -1) {
                    v = (c.$filters.eq(indx).find('.tablesorter-filter').val() || '').toLowerCase();
                    showRow = showRow || $(this).text().toLowerCase() === v;
                }
            });
            return showRow;
        };

    $table.tablesorter({
        theme: 'green',
        widgets: ['uitheme', 'zebra', 'columns', 'filter'],
        sortReset: true,
        sortRestart: true,
        widthFixed: true,
        widgetOptions: {
            filter_functions: {
                '.filter-OR': {
                    'Yes': filterfxn,
                    'No' : filterfxn
                }
            }
        }
    });
});
```

I've been working on the filter widget to make it more straight-forward, by adding a `data` parameter to the `filter_functions`. The same `data` passed to the [filter type functions](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/example-widget-filter-custom-search.html#how_to_add_custom_filter_types).

I know this looks messy, so I'm thinking about removing the extra parameters in a later update.

```js
filter_functions : {
  0 : function(e, n, f, i, $r, c, data) {} // <- parameters in the next update
  // 0 : function(c, data) {} // planned change (version undetermined)
}
```

