@agjs - A duplicate to this request (#8070) was closed, this request is actually still open (I make the same mistake rather frequently).  But considering there are 3,422 FontAwesome issues as I type this[1], and there are relatively few votes for this icon[2], we may be waiting for a while.  Thankfully @eaglejs has made an svg available for us to use in the meantime. :smile: 

[1] I suspect most of those are icon requests.
[2] For example, the request for a Free Code Camp icon has almost 250 +1s - #6927

I've found a way to work around this problem; I'm sharing it in case it saves someone else. Basically we want to keep FontAwesome 5 from thinking that every time we use `far` that it refers to Font Awesome. That's difficult, but the next best thing is it "undo" the Font Awesome effects in certain circumstances—here if the thing is an `<aside>` or a `<figure>`.

```css
aside.far, figure.far {
  /* compensate for Font Awesome 5 hijacking "far" */
  -webkit-font-smoothing: inherit;
  display: initial;
  font-family: inherit;
  font-style: inherit;
  font-variant: inherit;
  font-weight: inherit;
  text-rendering: inherit;
  line-height: inherit;
}
```

That's a hack, and it is somewhat brittle because it depends on knowing exactly what Font Awesome is doing (so that we can undo it), but on a positive note at least we can hide away this workaround in our stylesheet without mucking with our document source code.

I want to be clear that, although I believe this was a poor architectural decision by Font Awesome to hijack additional unqualified global CSS classes, I still think Font Awesome is a freakin' awesome product. I hope my misadventures and discoveries can help someone else overcome some of these problems.

@ryanpetrello 
I don't think the intent is "Secure" I think its obfuscation and as long as we don't tout it as being secure hopefully no one is under a false sense of security. 

Many companies I know just don't want "plain text passwords" in files but they don't say they require security. At a past company someone was telling me that something to the affect of: if someone has to do something to get a password (decrypt it, unencoded it, etc) it proves intent whereas "just seeing it" and using it could be interpreted as an accident (disclaimer: I'm not a lawyer).

Also, tokens will be cool as long as people have the automation to refresh the token. i.e. if someone was using Jenkins with TowerCLI (which hopefully they are using my plugin) they would need something to rotate Jenkins token (if they set it to expiring). Also, until people have migrated to a version of Tower which supports Tokens us telling them to use a token is kind of pointless. 

@AlanCoding 
When using TowerCLI via Ansible/Tower it makes sense to use a vaulted password/Tower credential and you don't need a config file so this change would be mute. When coding it, I actually thought about using a vaulted password in the config file but then we would need to require ansible libraries on the box. I also thought about actually encrypting the password as well but didn't want to require libcrypt or another library (plus were open source so we couldn't 'hide' the decryption key). As for other files within Ansible I would say "see above". At my client they don't even keep the Tower inventory file around after building a Tower cluster because it has unencrypted passwords in the file, it is only tolerated on the filesystem for the duration of the buildout.

