I agree, it would of been easier if they had just overloaded GatewayId with yet another use. I wonder why AWS didn't.

In addition to this code producing a CF template without an error, the `boto3.client.validate_template(TemplateBody=t.to_json())` also does not return any errors. This is a good problem for a validator because the only way to discover it is to actually build the stack and watch it rollback.

For troposphere to validate this would require "knowing" that the route resource will be used with either a NatGateway or IGW/VGW. In the troposhpere code, NatGatewayId, like most troposphere object's, attributes is just a `basestring`. Writing your solution as pseudo code:

```
for every Route resource:
    if it has a GatewayId:
        if the GatewayId setting is a NatGateway:
            return error
```

This seems easy if `GatewayId=<troposphere NatGateway obj>`, but if it is just a `string`, then I'm not sure how this can be discovered. What if the script is referencing a resource that already exists? Maybe the validation can only check when the attribute is set to an object.

@ischneider If we have another project that collides with the package name `planet`, that is a compelling enough reason to change the name.

I'm still not convinced about burying the version. Very often I (and I'm assuming others) check versions at the top level. Examining large libraries in the Python ecosystem, you'll notice that, for instance, `numpy.linalg` does not have a `__version__` property. Rather it exists on the top level (`numpy.__version__`). Same is true for scipy and scikit-learn, and many others.

That said, I'll yield the decision to you.

