@HonzaKral Using two queries is what I ended up doing. However, I first had to redesign the query to use abosulte instead of relative dates, to ensure I would actually be searching the same data set for both.

My suggestions for how to handle this would be to add a new function, `execute_scan()`, which returns a Response object like `execute()` does, only the `.hits` element is a `scan()`-style iterator instead of a list.

Alternately, instead of a new function, you could make it an adjustable property of the Search object itself, so `s = s.scroll(True); s.execute()` executes a scrolled query and returns a Response object with an iterable `.hits` element, while `s = s.scroll(False); s.execute()` executes a normal query and returns a Response object with a static `.hits` element.

